<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>


<section xml:id="lesson5_1" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Basic Probability</title>

  <p>In this chapter, we'll first review what probability means, and what it doesn't mean.
    Next, we'll learn how to combine probabilities for independent events.</p>

  <p>Throughout the chapter, we will explore probability using a common context in which you often
    encounter probabilities: weather forecasts. We will then apply it to the quantum context, in
    which we calculate the
    probability of measuring one, two, or more qubits in a particular state.</p>

  <section xml:id="sec-probability-meaning">
    <title>What a Probability Means</title>

    <p>What do weather forecasts really mean? Look at the weather forecast below and complete the
      exercise to identify what you can conclude about the forecast.</p>

    <image source="L5.1-weather-forecast.png" width="66%" />

    <exercise label="L5-1-Forecast-Events">
      <title>
        Probability in Forecasts
      </title>
      <idx>probability forecast</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>Which of the following statements is true based on the weather forecast?</p>

      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>It is not going to rain at 11pm.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>It is very unlikely to rain at 11pm, but it still might rain.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>It is going to rain at 4am.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>It might rain at 4a, but it might not rain.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>It is more likely to rain in the morning than in the evening.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Yes! However, there is still a possibility that it rains in the evening and not the
              morning.</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>

      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>Think carefully about what a forecast probability means.</p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>


    <p>
      What it really means is that if we experienced 100,000 days with these identical conditions,
      approximately 40,000 of them would have rain at 4am. However, it does not make a definitive
      statement about what is going to happen today.
</p>


    <sidebyside widths="50% 50%" valign="top">
      <p> Probability is <em>NOT:</em>
<ul>
          <li>Knowledge about the outcome of any individual event</li>
          <li>Confirmed or refuted through a single experiment</li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p> Probability is: <ul>
          <li>A prediction of the frequency of an outcome of many, many actions
</li>
          <li>Confirmed or refuted through many, many experiments</li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </sidebyside>
  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-independent-probabilities">
    <title>Combining Independent Probabilities</title>
    <p> Now that we understand what a probability means, we can learn how to combine probabilities
      for independent events.
      Two events are independent if the outcome of one event does not affect the outcome of the
      other event.
      For example, the outcome of a coin flip is independent of the outcome of another coin flip.</p>

    <p> Let's say we have two coins, and we flip both of them at the same time:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>What is the probability that the first coin will be heads?</li>
      <li>What is the probability that the second coin will be heads?</li>
    </ul>

    <p> Hopefully, in your head, you are calculating the probability of each coin being heads as <m>50\%</m>.
      We want to take that result and calculate the probability of both coins being heads at the
      same time.</p>
    <p>
      <image source="L5.1.onecoin.png" width="40%" />
    </p>
    <p> One way to reason about it is to list out all the possible outcomes of flipping two coins.
      Because each option is equally likely, the probability of each case is <m>25\%</m>. That means
      that the probability of both coins being heads is <m>25\%</m>. Likewise, the probability of both
      coins being tails is <m>25\%</m>.</p>
    <p> You might notice, though, that two of the choices look the same. That is, two choices have
      one heads and one tails. So the probability that "one coin is heads and the other coin is
      tails" is <m>50\%</m>, whereas the probability that "the first coin is heads and the second coin
      is tails" is <m>25\%</m>.</p>

    <p>
      <image source="L5.1.twocoins.png" width="66%" />
    </p>

    <p> This example was fairly simple because we had equal probabilities for each outcome. Let's go
      back to our
      weather example and look at how to calculate independent probabilities when the probabilities
      are not equal.</p>

    <p> Let's imagine that I am always running late in the morning, I'm groggy, and I'm just a
      little spacey, so I don't have a chance to look up the forecast. On any given day, I have a <m>25\%</m>
      chance of deciding to bring a raincoat, just in case. It turns out that a particular day has a <m>50\%</m>
      chance of raining. So I have the following scenario:</p>

    <p>
      <image source="L5.n-probs1.png" width="50%" />
    </p>

    <p> Notice that I drew the pictures based on the ratios: <m>\frac{3}{4}</m> chance of not bringing a
      raincoat, and <m>\frac{1}{4}</m> chance of bringing a raincoat is depicted as three shirts and one
      raincoat. This is similar to how we have been representing superposition probabilities with
      our visual representation.</p>

    <p>We can use this same approach to depict all of the possibilities, still repeating
      possibilities to indicate that they are more likely.
      I'll show the process in two steps.</p>

    <p>
      <image source="L5.n-probs2.png" width="66%" />
    </p>

    <p> We can see from the final picture (below) that the probability that I forget my rain jacket <em>
      AND</em> it being raining is <m>\frac{3}{8}</m>.</p>
    <p>
      <image source="L5.n-probs3.png" width="66%" />
    </p>


    <p>It turns out that we can actually do this with a simple calculation. Given our starting
      probabilities of <m>0.75</m> forgetting raincoat, <m>0.25</m> bringing raincoat, and <m>0.5</m> raining,
      we can calculate the probability of it raining <em>AND</em> forgetting raincoat as: <m>0.75 \times 0.5 = 0.375 = \frac{3}{8}.</m></p>
    <p>
      <image source="L5.n-probsmult.png" width="66%" />
    </p>

    <exercise label="L5.1_Q1">
      <title>Probability Practice #1</title>
      <idx>L5.1 Q1</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>You roll a six-sided die. What is the probability of rolling a 4?</p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{6}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{3}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{12}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </exercise>

    <exercise label="L5.1_Q2">
      <title>Probability Practice #2</title>
      <idx>L5.1 Q2</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>If you toss three coins, what is the probability of getting exactly two heads?</p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="yes">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{3}{8}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{4}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{1}{8}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </exercise>


    <p> If you want to learn just a little bit more about probabilities in this cartoon fashion,
      check out our zine at: <url href="https://www.epiqc.cs.uchicago.edu/probability">
      https://www.epiqc.cs.uchicago.edu/probability</url></p>


  </section>


</section>
